<h3>
    <strong>1. Columbia River (Lower Gorge Area &amp; Sauvie Island)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Oregon’s prime salmon fishery features strong <strong>spring Chinook</strong>, <strong>fall Chinook</strong>, and <strong>Coho salmon</strong> runs
    </li>
    <li>
        Popular access points include <strong>Sauvie Island beaches</strong>, <strong>Government Island</strong>, and launches near Troutdale and the <strong>Bonneville Dam</strong> 
    </li>
    <li>
        Techniques: trolling with herring or anchovies, using large spinners or plugs near river mouths&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>2. Willamette River (via Hillsboro to Portland, Oregon City Area)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Offers consistent <strong>spring Chinook</strong> runs in <strong>March–May</strong>, with fish congregating at structures upstream of Willamette Falls 
    </li>
    <li>
        Bank fishing: Milwaukie Bay Park, Sellwood, and Clackamette/Meldrum Bar parks near Oregon City 
    </li>
    <li>
        Effective methods include back‑bouncing eggs or spinners from shore or drifting near flow breaks&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>3. Clackamas River</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Not far from Hillsboro, this scenic tributary produces <strong>spring Chinook</strong>, <strong>Coho (Sept–Nov)</strong>, and <strong>summer steelhead</strong>
    </li>
    <li>
        Good bank access at <strong>Carver Park</strong>, <strong>Riverside Park</strong>, <strong>Barton Park</strong>, and <strong>Milo McIver State Park</strong> 
    </li>
    <li>
        Tactics: drift salmon eggs, plug and spinner setups&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>4. Sandy River (Troutdale Area)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Just east of Portland, this river sees <strong>spring Chinook (March–June)</strong>, <strong>fall runs</strong>, and regular <strong>Coho salmon</strong> in September–October 
    </li>
    <li>
        Access: <strong>Oxbow Regional Park</strong>, <strong>Dodge Park</strong>, <strong>Lewis &amp; Clark</strong>, and <strong>Dabney</strong> for bank and drift fishing
    </li>
    <li>
        Angler tips: target deep pools, log-run structure; use spinners, plugs, or bait setups
    </li>
</ul>
