<h2>
    Techniques &amp; Gear
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Trolling</strong>: Use fresh or flash-frozen <strong>herring</strong>, anchovies, or artificial bait near river mouths (Columbia, Willamette)
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Plunking / casting from shore</strong>: Effective for spring runs along the Willamette at Meldrum Bar and Clackamette Park; use <strong>spinners</strong>, <strong>plugs</strong>, or <strong>bobber + eggs</strong> setups 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Drift fishing</strong>: Use cured roe or yarn ties on Clackamas and Sandy Rivers, especially in deeper holding water and tailouts&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Licenses &amp; Regulations
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        You need an <strong>Oregon Angling License</strong> plus the <strong>Combined Angling Tag</strong> for salmon, steelhead, and sturgeon 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Columbia River Basin Endorsement</strong> also mandatory for Columbia and tributary fisheries (including Sandy River)
    </li>
    <li>
        Be aware of seasonal limits, gear restrictions, and closures (barbless hook rules, catch-and-release rules for wild salmon)&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Local Tips &amp; Commentary
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Oxbow Regional Park</strong> on the Sandy is a popular bank-fishing choice with good access and family-friendly amenities 
    </li>
    <li>
        Fall is particularly high-return season for <strong>Columbia tributaries</strong> like <strong>Sandy</strong> and <strong>Clackamas</strong>, often landing hatchery Chinook and Coho 
    </li>
    <li>
        For less-crowded fall kokanee/Chinook action, <strong>Clackamas upstream</strong> (Milo McIver or Barton) can be a quieter alternative to busier rivers&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Final Summary
</h2>
<p>
    From Hillsboro, your best salmon fishing within an easy drive includes:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Columbia River</strong> (Sauvie Island, Strike mouth zones): reliable runs spring and fall.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Willamette River</strong> (listen for springers near Oregon City and Gladstone parks).
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Clackamas River</strong>: superb fall Coho &amp; spring Chinook action with excellent bank access.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Sandy River</strong>: scenic, well-stocked, and very fishable in both spring and fall.
    </li>
</ul>

